Title: An Act Regarding the Required State of Mind Relating to Robbery
Official Title: An Act Regarding the Required State of Mind Relating to Robbery
Number of Sections: 1
Source: versions - Documents and Disposition
Media Type: application/pdf
Strikethrough Detection: 2 sections found

================================================================================

Section 1:
132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST REGULAR SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 1146
H.P. 751 House of Representatives, March 18, 2025
Reference to the Committee on Criminal Justice and Public Safety suggested and ordered
printed.
ROBERT B. HUNT
Clerk
Presented by Representative SINCLAIR of Bath.
Printed on recycled paper
1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 17-A MRSA §651, sub-§1, ¶B, as amended by PL 2017, c. 157, §1, is
3 further amended to read:
4 B. The actor intentionally or knowingly threatens to use force against any person
5 present or otherwise intentionally or knowingly places any person present in fear of the
6 imminent use of force with the intent:
7 (1) To prevent or overcome resistance to the taking of the property, or to the
8 retention of the property immediately after the taking; or
9 (2) To compel the person in control of the property to give it up or to engage in
10 other conduct that aids in the taking or carrying away of the property.
11 Violation of this paragraph is a Class B crime;
12 SUMMARY
1133 This bill amends Maine’s robbery statute in response to the new federal standard set
1144 by Counterman v. Colorado, 600 U.S. 66 (2023). The bill requires that an actor must
1155 intentionally or knowingly threaten a person while committing theft to have the culpable
1166 state of mind to be found criminally liable for robbery.
